ophically sophisticated reflection on the nature of the world and humanity's place within it. Ultimately, the Liezi sees the world as one of change and indeterminacy.Arguing for the Liezi's historical, philosophical, and literary significance, the contributors to this volume offer a fresh look at this text, using contemporary approaches and providing novel insights. The volume is unique in its attention to both philosophical and religious perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChinese literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Taoism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Taoist.2bisacsh1 aAmes, Roger T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarrett, T. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerthrong, John H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCline, Erin M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDippmann, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDippmann, Jeffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIvanhoe, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKohn, Livia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittlejohn, Ronnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittlejohn, Ronnie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMichael, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichey, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary